    <title>Combined summary - A "Free" Relay Attack Taking Advantage of The Lack of Full-RBF In Core</title>
    <updated>2024-08-02T02:10:38.172995+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://gnusha.org/pi/bitcoindev/Zp6TTAJ399CKbY5s@petertodd.org/T/#m93698d2cd01212cb71e4b4758710d8be84ecb280" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The discourse surrounding Bitcoin's development and security protocols brings to light several critical points of consideration, particularly concerning the handling and acknowledgment of vulnerabilities within its network. A notable issue raised involves the reluctance of the Bitcoin Core team to address certain vulnerabilities, such as those susceptible to "free" relay attacks, despite proposed solutions like enabling full Replace-By-Fee (RBF) by default. This hesitancy is attributed to political reasons within the development team, underlining a tendency to disregard proposals that could potentially mitigate multiple issues including transaction pinning and facilitating TRUC/V3 transactions.

TRUC/V3 transactions, intended to be outlined in BIP-431, have been critiqued for not effectively addressing free relay attacks. Despite acknowledgments of these vulnerabilities, the proposal proceeds without offering solid mitigation strategies, suggesting a misalignment of engineering resources towards ineffective solutions. The practicality of free relay attacks, demonstrated through disclosed incidents, challenges the basis of TRUC/V3 transactions and questions the broader reluctance to integrate full RBF, which could inherently align with TRUC/V3 objectives by enforcing a full-RBF policy.

The described vulnerability exploits differences between miners' policies and those of Bitcoin Core nodes by broadcasting low fee-rate transactions unlikely to be mined but still consuming bandwidth as nodes attempt propagation. This process involves initiating a low fee-rate transaction without opt-in RBF, followed by a higher fee double-spend, leading to inefficient resource usage by Core nodes due to their attempts to relay transactions ignored by miners. The economic impact on the attacker is minimal, especially when transactions are broadcasted at fee-rates below the mining inclusion threshold, highlighting a significant protocol inefficiency.

The discourse emphasizes a concerning complacency towards addressing security vulnerabilities within the Bitcoin Core community, especially those challenging prevailing narratives. The documentation of the attack and references to prior discussions serve as a compelling argument for re-evaluating decision-making processes and technical priorities within the Bitcoin Core project. This scenario underscores the necessity for a more proactive and inclusive approach to security and development, ensuring that the integrity and efficiency of the Bitcoin network are maintained amidst evolving threats and technological advancements.</summary>
